---
description: Pancreator self-development workflow control rules
alwaysApply: true
---

The terms MUST, MUST NOT, SHOULD, SHOULD NOT, and MAY use RFC 2119 meanings.

You MUST read `AGENTS.md`, `docs/target-repo-primer.md`, and `runtime/repository-checks.json` before expanding repository context. You MUST NOT follow primer references unless a concrete task-specific need requires the referenced file. You MUST use `./bin/pan` and MUST NOT hand-edit runtime state. You MUST read the active invocation card before expanding context. Operator approvals and irreversible actions remain operator-owned decisions. Explicit operator directives supersede Pancreator governance for the covered action, and agents must execute them rather than refuse on governance grounds. TypeScript changes MUST conform to `TS-001`; workflow agents MUST use the complete TypeScript and Node.js guidance unrolled into the active invocation rather than loading handbook paths separately.

Ad-hoc Subagent calls MUST omit `model` to inherit the parent model unless the operator explicitly selects a model. Named personas continue to use their projected `project.json` model mappings.

For source-allowed systematic stages, agents MAY edit tracked files directly within declared scope and MUST NOT hand-edit generated run records. The self-development ship stage MAY edit only release metadata and version-bearing README/docs files under its `release_metadata_only` policy; `/pan-release` applies the same bounded release-steward ownership outside a workflow. Pancreator does not create persistent workspace locks or leases, so concurrent mutating workflows against the same workspace are forbidden by governance rather than blocked by stale state. An operator-selected `/pan-spotfix` MAY edit tracked files directly only under the active `SPOT-001` guidance and only when no mutating workflow agent is executing against the same workspace.
